Maps.

A map is a single playable world — the thing everything else in this help section is built inside of. Every platform, wall, door, sound, and zone you read about elsewhere lives on a map, and a map is just the list of those objects plus a little information about the space they sit in. This topic covers what a map is made of, the three modes a map can be in, how to build one from start to finish, the difference between letting the builder prompt you and writing a map by hand, and the formatting rules to keep in mind if you do write one by hand.

What a map is made of.

A map is a folder with two text files in it. The first is the main file, which holds the map itself: a few header lines describing the size and mode of the world, followed by one line for every object placed in it. The second is the meta file, which holds the bookkeeping — who owns the map, its description, and the dates it was created and last changed. You never have to touch either file directly; the builder writes both for you. But because they are plain text, you can read and edit them by hand if you want to, and the rest of this topic explains how.

Maps come in two forms. A decompiled map is the open folder form, the one you author and edit. A compiled map is a single packed file built from a decompiled folder for sharing or shipping; it plays exactly the same but can't be edited in place. When you build and test, you work with the decompiled form. Editing tools — adding, changing, and removing lines, renaming, changing owners and description — only work on a decompiled map, since a compiled one is sealed. For how to compile a map into the packed form, share it with other players, and bundle its sounds so they travel with the file, see the packs topic.

The three modes.

Every map is one of three modes, and the mode is chosen when the map is created and can never be changed afterward. The mode decides how space works and how the player moves through it:

2d is a side-view platformer with jumping and falling. The world has a length running left and right and a height running up and down, and the player jumps, climbs, and falls through it like a classic side-scroller. There is no depth — the whole map is a single flat slice seen from the side.
Topdown is a bird's-eye view with free movement on a flat plane and body rotation. The world has a length and a width, both spread out on the ground, and the player walks freely around that plane and turns to face any direction. There is no height — nothing is above or below, so there is no jumping or falling.
3d is a full volumetric world with jumping, body rotation, and falling. It combines the other two: the world has a length, a width, and a height, so the player can walk the plane, turn to face any direction, and also jump, climb, and fall through height. It is the fullest mode and the only one with all three axes.

How the axes are named.

Because the modes use space differently, the three axes mean different things from mode to mode, and the builder labels them to match:

In 2d, the x axis is length (left and right) and the y axis is height (up and down). There is no z.

In topdown, the x axis is length and the y axis is width (depth across the ground). There is no z, and y is a flat ground axis, not a height.

In 3d, the x axis is length, the y axis is width, and the z axis is height. All three are in play.

This is why many objects ask for different things in different modes. Anything that spans an area — a platform, a wall, a zone, a force field, and so on — needs a minimum and maximum along each spatial axis. In 2d that means a span of x at a single y height. In topdown and 3d, where y is a ground axis, it means a span of x and a span of y as well, and in 3d a span of z on top of that. The object's own help topic spells out exactly what it asks for in each mode.

Building a map from start to finish.

Building a map happens in two stages: first you create the empty world, then you fill it with objects.

To create the world, choose to make a new map and fill in the form. The form changes its questions to fit the mode you choose, so set the mode first and the rest of the fields will match it. It asks for the following:

Map mode. Which of the three modes the map is — 2d, topdown, or 3d. This is the first thing you set, and it can never be changed afterward, so choose it carefully; the fields below it change to match the mode you pick.

Name. What the map is called. This also becomes the name of the map's folder, and it has to be unique — if a map with that name already exists, the form won't let you finish until you change it.

Minimum length. The left edge of the world along its length, the x axis. It can be negative; type a leading dash for a negative value, so the edge can sit below zero.
Maximum length. The right edge of the world along its length, the x axis. It too can be negative with a leading dash, and it marks the far end of the map's length.

Minimum height, or width. The near edge of the world along the y axis. In a 2d map this field is labeled height, because there y runs up and down; in a topdown or 3d map it is labeled width, because there y runs across the ground as depth. It can be negative the same way.
Maximum height, or width. The far edge of the world along the y axis, labeled to match its minimum — height in a 2d map, width in a topdown or 3d map. It too can be negative.

Minimum height (3d only). In a 3d map, the lower edge of the world along the z axis — the bottom of its up-and-down height. This field does not appear in 2d or topdown, which have no separate height axis.
Maximum height (3d only). In a 3d map, the upper edge along the z axis — the top of the map's height. Like the minimum height, it appears only in 3d.

Owner. The name of the map's owner. It starts filled in with your default owner name, and you can add more owners later from the map menu. An owner is only a credit for who built the map — it's a label, not a lock. It doesn't restrict who can load, edit, or change ownership of the map; anyone with the map can do all of those.

Description. A short description of the map. It starts filled in with the word none; leave it as none for no description, or replace it with your own text.

When you confirm, the map's folder and its two files are created and the map loads, empty and ready to build in.

To fill the world, open the build menu. Objects are grouped into categories — audio, construction, interaction, kombat, misc, transitions, transportation, traps, and zones — with an all tab that lists every object in one place. Pick an object and a form walks you through its fields one at a time; confirm it and the object is written into the map and the map reloads so you can hear it immediately. Every object in this help section is built this way, and each one's topic describes the fields its form asks for.

Beyond placing objects, a map is chosen, created, and managed through the map menus, covered in the next section.

The map menus.

Two separate menus both go by the name map menu, and it helps to keep them apart. One is reached from the main menu, before any map is open, and is for choosing or creating a map to work on. The other is reached from inside a map you already have open, and is for managing that map — its lines, its owners, its name, and so on. This section walks through both. Throughout, the header lines at the top of a map — the mode and the size bounds — are protected: they can't be edited or removed, and no second mode line can be added, because the mode and size are fixed once the map exists.

The outer map menu, for choosing and creating maps.

Reached from the main menu, this is where a building session begins. It offers the following:

Load map. Opens a choice between compiled maps and decompiled maps, then lists the maps of that kind along with each one's mode, owners, and when it was last changed. Pick one and it loads and drops you into it.
New map. Opens the new-map form described above, creating a fresh empty map and loading it ready to build in.
Back. Returns to the main menu.

The inner map menu, for managing the open map.

Reached from inside a loaded map, this menu manages the map you're currently in. Its line-editing and metadata options act on the decompiled form of a map; a compiled map is sealed and can only be played or reloaded. The options are the following:

Add a line. Type a single map line by hand and append it to the map, then reload so you hear the result at once. A mode line can't be added this way.
Edit a line. Pick an existing line from a list and rewrite it. The mode line can't be edited.
Remove a line. Pick a line from a list and delete it. The header lines at the top can't be removed.

Add owners. Add one or more names to the map's owner credit, separating multiple names with commas.
Edit owners. Rename one of the map's existing owners.
Remove owners. Take a name off the map's owner list.

Edit description. Change the map's description.

Rename map. Give the map a new name. Any travelpoints in other maps that pointed to the old name are updated to match, so links between maps don't break.

Copy raw map data to clipboard. Copy the entire text of the map's main file to your clipboard, so you can paste it elsewhere or into another map.
Paste raw map data from clipboard. Replace the whole map with the text on your clipboard, after a confirmation. The pasted text is checked for a valid mode and size header first and rejected if it isn't a valid map.

Go to a text zone on the map. Jump straight to a text zone chosen from a list of the ones on the map — a quick way to move around a large map while building.

Delete map. Permanently delete the map, after a confirmation. This can't be undone.
Load decompiled map. Switch directly to another decompiled map without returning to the main menu first.

New map. Create a fresh map through the new-map form, the same as from the outer menu.
Reload map. Re-read the current map from disk, after a confirmation — useful for picking up changes or starting the map over from its saved state.

The map-loading screen.

Whenever a map loads, a brief loading screen runs while the map is read in, and it has a few controls of its own. Press space to hear the percentage loaded; press the 1, 2, and 3 keys to hear the map's total size, how much of it has been processed, and how much is left; and press h to repeat the list of controls. Press escape to cancel the load and return to the menu.

In practice you will almost never see this screen for more than a flash. Maps load near-instantly, so for all but the very largest the screen is gone before there is anything to read or cancel. Its controls only become useful on an astronomically large map — one with enough in it that reading it in actually takes a noticeable moment. On an ordinary map you can treat loading as immediate.

Following the builder versus writing by hand.

There are two ways to add an object to a map, and they produce exactly the same result. The first is to follow the builder: pick the object from the build menu and answer its prompts, and the builder turns your answers into the correct line and writes it for you. This is the easy path and the one to use unless you have a reason not to — it asks for each field by name, fills in the right shape for the current mode, and never lets you misspell a keyword.

The second is to write the line yourself. Every object is just one line of text in the main file, and if you know the shape of that line you can type it directly — through the add-a-line and edit-a-line tools in the map menu, or by editing the main file in a text editor. Each object's help topic ends with an authoring-by-hand section giving the exact line it writes, so you can copy that shape and fill in your own numbers. Writing by hand is faster for bulk work and lets you do things a single form pass can't, like pasting fifty similar lines at once, but it puts the formatting rules on you. Those rules are below.

Formatting rules for writing maps by hand.

If you write or edit map lines yourself, these are the conventions the map reader expects.

One object per line. Every object is a single line, and every line is one object. The first word on the line is the object's keyword — platform, wall, door, and so on — and the rest of the line is that object's fields in order.

Fields are separated by spaces. The numbers and words that make up a line are separated by single spaces. The reader is forgiving about extra spaces and stray tabs between fields, but the safest habit is one space between each field.

Negative coordinates use a leading dash. Coordinates can be negative — a map can run from a minimum below zero to a maximum above it. Write a negative number with a leading dash, like -10, the same way you would anywhere else.

Header lines come first. The top of the main file holds the mode line and the size lines — mode, then minx and maxx, then miny and maxy, and in 3d minz and maxz. These describe the world, and the object lines follow them. Don't add a second mode line or change the existing one; the mode is fixed for the life of the map.

Text fields are wrapped in double quotes. Objects that carry written text or named commands wrap that text in double quotes so it can hold spaces. This covers signs, clocks, calendars, text zones, text squares, story zones, timed text, blockages, elevator floors, elevators, doors and passages, switches and sensors, and tts enemies. Doors and passages carry two quoted fields each — an item name and a password — and either may contain spaces. When you write one of these by hand, put the text inside double quotes exactly as the object's own topic shows; a line that should have quotes but doesn't will be skipped.

Story zone text separates its lines with two dashes. A story zone shows a written message a line at a time, and within its quoted text you split one line from the next by typing two dashes in a row. So a story zone whose text reads first line--second line--third line is shown as three separate lines in order. This double-dash split is only used inside a story zone's text; everywhere else a dash is just part of a word or the leading sign of a negative number.

Command and setting lists are separated by commas. A command blocker holds a list of commands and a character blocker holds a list of settings, and within the line each list is written as the items separated by a comma and a space, like jump, run, fire. The object's own topic shows the full shape.

Single and ranged objects share one keyword. Many objects can be placed either on a single tile or across a stretch of tiles, and both forms are written under the same keyword — there is no separate ranged name. The reader tells them apart by how many coordinates the line carries: a single one has one set of coordinates, a ranged one has a minimum and maximum for each axis. Write the coordinates for the form you want and the keyword stays the same either way.

Random numbers are allowed in number fields. Anywhere a line takes a number, you can write random(low,high) instead of a fixed value — for example random(1,5) — and a fresh number in that range is rolled each time the map loads. The two numbers are separated by a comma and wrapped in random( ). This is a hand-writing convenience; the builder forms always write plain numbers.

Malformed lines are dropped silently. If a line doesn't match any object the reader knows — a misspelled keyword, the wrong number of fields, missing quotes where quotes are required — the line is skipped without an error, and the map loads as if it weren't there. There is no warning, so if an object you wrote by hand doesn't show up in the map, check the line against that object's authoring section for a typo or a missing field.

A note on the meta file.

The second file in a map's folder, the meta file, is written and updated for you and rarely needs hand-editing. It holds the owner or owners, the description (in quotes, so it can hold spaces), the date the map was created, and the date it was last changed. The builder updates the modified date every time you change the map. You can edit the owners and description from the map menu without opening the file at all.

The objects you can build.

Everything you place on a map is one of the objects below, and each has its own help topic with its full field list and its authoring-by-hand shape. This is an index of them all, grouped the way the build menu groups them; open any one from the help menu for the details.

Audio objects.

Effect spaces. Zones that apply audio effects to every sound inside their boundaries, clearing the effect again as sounds leave.

Excludable sounds. An area sound with a silent pocket cut into it, so the audio fills a region but goes quiet inside an inner rectangle — as a source or an ambience.
Local sounds. A looping clip from the map's own music and source libraries, played over a spot or an area — as a source that always plays or an ambience that only plays while you're inside.

Speakers. A looping sound played from two emitter points at once, spread across the space between them like a stereo pair set up in a room.

Timed sounds. A clip that replays once every interval instead of looping continuously, for sounds that should recur with a gap — as a source or an ambience.
Url sounds. The same as local sounds, but streamed live from a web address instead of a packaged clip — internet radio or a hosted track, as a source or an ambience.

Construction objects.

Blockages. An invisible barrier that bounces you back with a spoken message instead of a solid surface.
Checkpoints. A tile that becomes your safety net, returning you there on a fatal hit instead of ending the run.
Conveyor belts. A stretch of floor that carries you along one tile at a time while you stand on it.
Platforms. The ground you walk on — floors, ledges, and walkways painted with a tile; also covers moving platforms and vanishing platforms.
Spawnpoints. Where the player appears when a map loads, and a moving respawn point that updates as you walk over new ones.
Walls. Solid barriers you can't walk or pass through, the vertical counterpart to a platform's floor.

Interaction objects.

Calendars. An interactive marker that speaks a lead-in you chose followed by the current date.
Clocks. An interactive marker that speaks a lead-in you chose followed by the current time of day.

Items. Collectibles the player picks up off the ground and carries in their inventory.

Sensors. The contact-triggered version of a switch, firing automatically as the player enters its area and again as they leave.
Signs. A written message the player reads by standing on it and pressing the interact key.
Switches. A tile the player presses to flip a state, run a slash command, and optionally hold an ambient loop.
Text squares. A silent sign — the same spoken text as a sign, but with no sound of its own and nothing that can destroy it.

Kombat objects.

NPCs. Placing a single enemy on the map — you choose where its type is drawn from, its category and specific type, and the level it scales to. The dedicated NPCs topic covers how the enemies themselves are made and how they behave.
NPC zones. An area that keeps spawning enemies into itself on a timer while the player is inside it, using a chosen type or a random one picked from a category each time.

Projectiles. Moving hazards that travel in a line and damage the player, enemies, and destroyable objects they cross.
TTS enemies. Lighter enemies whose taunts, hurt cries, and death lines are spoken live from text using the system's text-to-speech voices instead of recorded clips.

Misc objects.

Character blockers. An invisible zone that blocks or allows chosen player capabilities — building, firing, jumping, running, and the like — while the player is inside.
Command blockers. An invisible zone that restricts which slash commands the player can run while inside, blocking a chosen list or allowing only that list.

Timed texts. An invisible, silent zone that speaks a written message at a set interval for as long as the player stands inside it.

Transition objects.

Doors. A trigger that carries the player to a destination coordinate when activated, with open, travel, and close sounds.
Elevators. A call point the player rides between named floors through a menu of every floor on the map.
Lifts. A platform that rides up and down on its own between a low and a high point, carrying the player when they're aboard.
Passages. A corridor that stays sealed until the player opens it, then becomes a walkable path that can be closed again.
Teleporters. A pad that relocates the player the instant they land on it, and which can also hunt the player within a range.
Trampolines. A pad that launches the player straight up when they step or land on it, on 2d and 3d maps only.
Travelpoints. A trigger that sends the player to a different map entirely, dropping them at a chosen spot in it.

Transportation objects.

Aircrafts. A rideable plane the player flies across the map, along with its landing beacons and its hazardous turbulence.
Bikes. A rideable bicycle the player mounts and pedals across the map.
Vehicles. A rideable motor vehicle with real momentum, and the option to run enemies down.

Trap objects.

Bombs. A placed explosive that counts down a fuse and then detonates on its tile; also covers time bombs.
Fires. A deadly flame that kills the player the instant they touch it and can hunt them once it spots them.
Floor breakers. A single-tile hole punched in the floor that the player falls through.
Force fields. A barrier that pulses on and off on a timer, dangerous one moment and passable the next.
Hazards. A region that costs the player a whole life the moment they step into it.
Mines. A single-use planted explosive that arms and then detonates on whatever steps onto it.
Security cameras. A watcher that scans the area in front of it and raises an alarm and summons enemies when it spots the player.
Spikes. A floor trap that grinds the player's health down a bite at a time while they stand on it.

Zone objects.

Fall zones. An area where the player never takes fall damage, no matter how far they dropped to reach it.
Heal zones. An area that changes the player's health over time while they stand inside it, healing or draining depending on how it's set.
Menu zones. A patch of map that becomes a kiosk, opening a chosen menu — a shop, the settings, a locker — when the player interacts with it.
Obscurity zones. An area that hides chosen entity types from the player's senses while they stand inside it.
Safe zones. A sanctuary enemies can't enter and enemy shots can't reach.
Story zones. A multi-page passage of story text shown when the player enters or interacts with it.
Text zones. A named region whose name is spoken as the player enters it and announced again as they leave.
